It's called pasteurization. Basically cows can carry body fluid borne diseases (originally it was smallpox I believe) that would spread to humans through drinking an infected cow's milk.
It's not filtering, it's raising the milk to a certain temperature for a certain amount of time without boiling it to kill off those pathogens.

Raw milk is 100% good for you, but in terms of food safety standards, it's too dangerous to allow shops to sell it.

Essentially correct. I would add that milk at body temperature is pretty much an ideal growth medium for lots and lots of bacteria. If the cow is healthy the milk will come out sterile. "If." There aren't always immediately obvious symptoms. Plus a cow's udders are sometimes so distended that they drag on the ground, especially if she is an older cow, and pick up fecal matter and a whole lot of other stuff. So pasteurization was invented. It took some experimentation to find a temperature that would kill bacteria without making the milk taste burnt or picking up off-flavors from cooking it. Different countries have different regulatory standards, and in some countries--I believe they do this in some parts of Europe--milk is packaged and sealed in cans without pasteurization, then irradiated to kill the bacteria. The tools used can be anything from ingots of cobalt 60 or cesium 137 to yuge and powerful X-ray machines. In some countries they use the term "cold pasteurization" because a lot of people believe from things they see in sci-fi movies that it is appropriate to respond with flailing screaming panic when they hear the word "radiation." There are experiments with using ultraviolet light also, but some food products are fairly opaque to it.
